I had to take an IQ test for a psychological evaluation to see what accommodations I needed as a person on the autism spectrum. Before taking the IQ test and getting the results, I believed I was dumb and slow. I even believed that other kids were smarter than me. When I got my IQ test results, my IQ turned out to be 83 (low average). After getting the results, I knew I was stupid.
As someone with a Low Average IQ, I do not act like the smartest person in the room. I feel stupid and I am aware of my stupidity. Not only do I have a pretty low IQ, but I also have severe Generalized Anxiety Disorder. As someone on the autism spectrum, I would worry about everything and anything. I also have reading comprehension and math deficits.
Despite this, I did well in college because I worked hard and had substantial support. Furthermore, I loved to learn even though I had an IQ of 83. For instance, I would join my college debate team to challenge myself and intellectually stimulate myself. I also joined my college debate team to work on thinking faster. Hey, you've mentioned the Dunning-Kruger-effect almost at the end of the video. Just curious - why didn't you just name it?^^ Whats kind of interesting and this might upset people - I was full of doubt about my intelligence and I was always quite in the lower average spectrum in school, but as soon as I kind of woke up and finished my a-levels in the beginning of my 20s I actually developed a certain level of higher marks. I was wondering and went for a psychologist and he sent me to an IQ test. And from that point in time I knew why I was feeling quite uncommon. I got 135 points in the first test, reaching around 150 in the latest test. This did not help me with my low self esteem but explained a lot why I was thinking about stuff others don't. So, to sum it up, I don't feel superior to others - I just feel to be another way. Many people have emotional skills way above mine, some have more creativity or are better in fixing stuff. I actually believe that the only thing that more intelligent people should do is not only to invent new stuff, but try to improve the core-skills of everyone surrounding them. (Like my brother. He is "not the sharpest tool in the shed" , but we found out what he could do best - find problems of cars. So my brother and I ended up in the garage every evening, fixing stuff or improving things of my car and thats fantastic now. He is the better mechanic, I am better in calculating things.)

In the end, thanks for the video, but everyone who is out of the "normal spectrum" - just don't feel bad about it, it could be something wonderful that furfills you. Have a good night ;)

Level of formal education is not a numerical value. Like you can't say someone with a degree is above (better) and someone without is below  (worse) unless you are assuming that having a higher level degree is unequivocally of higher value than not having one. In a perfect world that may be true but having a degree does not at all mean you are more intelligent, educated, mature, knowledgeable, or successful, it's just a piece of paper from a trusted third party saying you can do a certain thing. Like having a medical doctorate does not make you above someone with a bachelors in engineering, you just had different schooling On a side note, plenty of high school drop outs become more successful and intelligent than you or I could ever hope to be. I just think it's harmful to suggest that having a degree is an absolute positive and not having one is an absolute negative on a number line.

Well, as far degrees: 2 X bachelors (Molecular Biology/Biochemistry & Chemical Physics), Masters in Theoretical Chemistry, & a Ph.D Chemical Physics.

Took me close to 8 years to get my 1st bachelors between partying that lead to my daughter and I was activated several times while in the military. Overall, I'm not smart because I have to work so hard in understanding anything. Group theory in physics and theoretical chemistry, for some reason, was difficult even thou I found linear algebra to be easy.

Height: 5'6 Yea, it sucks.

I.Q.: I was tested at 140 as soon as I graduated (at age 32). Overall, I believe I.Q. testing doesn't have the significance that most people tend to think it has. I've meet people with astonishing high I.Q.'s that have pretty crazy beliefs that are plagued with double think. In all truth, I know I'm about average but just have a tenacity to work hard. People, in general, are not able to discern the difference between intelligence and hard work. Well, unless you personally know that person.

Health: I can easily bench press 300lbs. My weight is approximately 165-170lbs. I have about 7-10% body fat. I'm a weightlifter, power lifter, and I run on average about 18 miles per week and I'm at the gym 8 hours a week.

I don't read books hardly at all. I do read textbooks, however.

While some will say that I'm intelligent, have a very "nice" body, and I'm a college professor that I'm lucky. What most people don't realize is the time and energy that are spent training and studying. No one has it all. At times, I go through long periods of time without seeing anyone. That's the price that has to be paid for the things I desire. So, in hindsight, amongst the majority of people I work with, while I'm good looking and have the appearance of being smart, I'm not a player, and I get stressed while learning new subjects because of the time it takes me to learn new subjects.

So even when you have above average metrics, it doesn't tell you the full story. Like not being able to go out with your friends and drink because you have to be at the gym at 5:00 a.m. (which means you have to wake up for 4:30 a.m.). Or not being able to date because of the time spent driving 5-6 hours week picking up and dropping off your daughter to make sure her needs are meet first. I will say, while have a daughter with a fling has costly me dearly (financially, professionally, and a slew of other metrics), being a dad has been the greatest gift at all. While my daughter can be a pain and I can be strict, it's wonderful to know that she knows without a shadow of doubt, I love her more than life itself. Hey, that's OK.

I would hope that I'm average. Many would say I'm above average but when you take the entirety of my all life... well, in many cases, I'm below average.
